    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4088322002" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4088322002" />
    <a title="Ricky Schneider" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/117577393-ricky-schneider"><img alt="Ricky Schneider" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609800191p2/117577393.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4088322002?book_show_action=true">Jun 30, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ricky Schneider" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ricky Schneider" href="/user/show/117577393-ricky-schneider">Ricky Schneider</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19937130-the-sound-of-waves">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4088322002" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14694336354446746270">Did I just read a Mishima novel that was ..wholesome, sweet, and romantic? What a beautiful surprise! Mishima&apos;s writing is usually brooding, ominous, and even morbid. This is quite the exception! There are only hints of his typical dark obsessions hidden sparingly beneath this simple love story set in a Japanese fishing village on a sleepy little island. The Sound of Waves is Mishima applying all his many gifts to a timeless tale of young love, small-town drama, and nautical adventure. <br/><br/> The stor</span>
  <span id="freeText14694336354446746270" style="display:none">Did I just read a Mishima novel that was ..wholesome, sweet, and romantic? What a beautiful surprise! Mishima's writing is usually brooding, ominous, and even morbid. This is quite the exception! There are only hints of his typical dark obsessions hidden sparingly beneath this simple love story set in a Japanese fishing village on a sleepy little island. The Sound of Waves is Mishima applying all his many gifts to a timeless tale of young love, small-town drama, and nautical adventure. <br /><br /> The story takes place almost entirely in a small fishing village on an idyllic island in Japan. Since losing power from a failed generator, the village is lit only by oil lamps and candles. The entire island, like the story itself, seems lost in time. It's as if the novel could be taking place in ancient Japan just as easily as it could be in 2021. The evocative language that is so indicative of Mishima brings every dew drop and ship sail to vivid life. We follow the characters through pine forests, waterfalls, rocky beaches, ancient temples, and cliffside lighthouses. I loved getting lost with them in this stunningly rendered world.<br /><br /> Our main protagonist is Shinji, a young fisherman being raised by a single mother on the island. He is eager, optimistic and hard-working but lives a relatively uneventful life until a new girl arrives on the island and shakes things up. Her name is Hatsue and she is, of course, beautiful but also tenacious and a talented diver. It's not a spoiler to say that they fall in love but the many nefarious and meddlesome townspeople make things difficult for them as Hatsue's father decides who she will be betrothed to. There is a memorable villain and even an unexpectedly loveable side character that I really enjoyed. <br /><br /> The writing is top-notch. Every moment is filled with mesmerizing imagery and crystal clear detail. Mishima somehow avoids his tendency toward the morose and writes with the innocence of youth and the unbridled optimism of a romantic. There is one sequence where he indulges a bit in his obsession with breasts but that was almost comical and also worked from Shinji's inexperienced, amorous perspective.<br /> <br />It wouldn't be Mishima without layer upon layer of metaphor and meaning infused into the story. I'm sure I didn't even scratch the surface of his subtext but I marked the pages multiple times (which I rarely do) noting unforgettable lines and cinematic scenes. The prose is packed with majestic descriptions, gorgeous imagery and indelible moments. I have no doubt that I will be returning to this beautiful and romantic tale again and again. For now, it lingers like a dream in my mind and has filled my heart with hope and happiness.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14694336354446746270" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

