  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3616652814" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3616652814" />
    <a title="Tim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/37256808-tim"><img alt="Tim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1444088588p2/37256808.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3616652814?book_show_action=true">Oct 27, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tim" href="/user/show/37256808-tim">Tim</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/37256808-tim?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3616652814" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15202827881287513328">I went through a phase of being very interested in the work of the brilliant, notorious Japanese author Mishima. He lived a fascinating and troubled life, which came to a very strange and violent end. I won&apos;t recap it all here, but he is well worth reading about. He wrote excellent, classic prose that translated very well into English, which was what he intended, according to a Japanese friend of mine. Most of his tales delve into dark and troubled areas of Japanese life, e.g.: a troubled monk w</span>
  <span id="freeText15202827881287513328" style="display:none">I went through a phase of being very interested in the work of the brilliant, notorious Japanese author Mishima. He lived a fascinating and troubled life, which came to a very strange and violent end. I won't recap it all here, but he is well worth reading about. He wrote excellent, classic prose that translated very well into English, which was what he intended, according to a Japanese friend of mine. Most of his tales delve into dark and troubled areas of Japanese life, e.g.: a troubled monk who burns down a beautiful temple, a successful older couple who turn on each other and whose marriage begins to crumble, idealistic right wing revolutionaries who plot to overthrow the government, and people who are unable to express their love for each other. <br /><br />So this book was a real shock. It is a lovely tale of youthful romance, set in an island fishing village, and it paints an attractive picture of hard-working, decent, traditional Japanese working people. None of this had any connection to the author's actual life. He was urban, intellectual, sophisticated, and a closeted homosexual. This was Mishima's second novel, and I can't help thinking that he wrote it in an effort to pen a popular novel that would put him on the literary map. Apparently he succeeded, and it is a very likeable book, that would probably be a good choice for a high school course. While reading it, I did often feel transported to the simple life of the fictional island of Uta-jima. <br /><br />(Spoiler alert) The story concerns a young fisherman, Shinji, who, over the course of the book, begins to fall in love with Hatsue, the niece of the richest man in town, a gruff ship-owner. There is a sensual scene in which the two of them end up alone together in a rainstorm and begin some sexual exploration. But there are obstacles to their union. An unpleasant young man also has his eye on Hatsue, and our young hero must contend with this rival, and also prove himself worthy. You won't find much of the later Mishima in this book (except in the quality of the prose), but it is an enjoyable read.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15202827881287513328" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


